        "created_at": "2025-12-22T16:12:44.054Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Hi everyone, I’m building a small IoT system where ESP32 sensors detect events (like motion or environmental changes) and need to notify users securely via Signal messages. I know Signal itself handles end-to-end encryption for chats, but I’m unsure what the best pattern is for bridging IoT alerts into a Signal workflow without exposing keys or backend credentials. For context, I’ve been following this ESP32 cloud post example: <a href=\"https://www.theengineeringprojects.com/2022/02/sending-data-to-cloud-with-esp32-and-thingspeak.html\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">https://www.theengineeringprojects.com/2022/02/sending-data-to-cloud-with-esp32-and-thingspeak.html</a>. It shows how ESP32 can push sensor readings to a cloud service over HTTP. I’ve also seen Arduino forum threads where people post sensor data to webhooks or dashboards, and Raspberry Pi community discussions about using MQTT or web services to relay alerts. For those who’ve tied IoT events to messaging platforms or bots (especially Signal via bots or APIs), what approach worked best for secure authentication and low-latency webhooks, server polling, third-party bots, or something else?</p>",
